Decent port. Interface and controls are clean and mostly responsive. It is hard to complain about being able to carry FF5 around in your pocket without a GBA and cart. The only "problem" people may have with this port is the sprites. They look a bit silly but are mostly fine. I personally prefer the chunkier 16-bit sprites, but I learned to deal with these. They don't clash with the backgrounds like they do in FF6. This is a great game with awesome mechanics and a fun, if shallow, story.

This port is phenomenal. Sure, the graphics are a bit different. I don't like the sprites of the characters, but seeing all new spell effects was worth paying the price. Also, people are complaining about a bug in Moogle Village. THERE IS NOT A BUG. You have to wait a good while outside Mogs tree for the sequence to start. Sometimes it's 30 seconds. Sometimes it's 5 minutes. It was like that in the original. I got past it by being *patient* and not constantly leaving and reentering places. This is the first game from Square that I have purchased since FFX, and it's well worth it. I just wish the FFVI port took some pointers...

As far as the gameplay is concerned, this is the most fun I've had out of 
any Final Fantasy title, largely thanks to it's job system. The only games 
I find to be more well rounded in the series are 9 and 6. I simply love 
this game. I also find V's music to be among Uematsu's best.

When the Game is running it is an excellent port and still as fun as the 
original. However, the game has an online drm check which will prevent you 
from playing if it cannot contact Square's servers. Even if it's the 
servers that are unresponsive. Beyond that, the graphics update and switch 
to an active battle system may rub those looking for nostalgia the wrong 
way, but overall it doesn't impact the core gameplay all that much. Except 
for the new character portraits, they're atrocious. If you are a fan of old 
school JRPGs and haven't played FFV, it deserves your attention. You might 
have to end up playing it on IOS or PC however.

UPDATE: I was pretty harsh on the Squeenix FF titles in previous comments but I finally came back and tried the game again after several updates and they have done everything we've asked for and more! The game has great controller support now (using the Nvidia Shield). And they added a very well made cloud sync for save files so you can sync your adventure between devices! Thanks for listening Squenix!  OLD: The game could be so great but Squeenix continues to screw up their Android games.    - No controller support.   - Touch controls are clunky and uncomfortable and no option for a fixed dpad.   - No game sync or cloud sync between devices.   - Numerous bugs with losing saves or game crashing.   - Outrageous price for a lacking game. The game looks fantastic and they did a great job updating the look while not changing too much. But they have to cover all the bases if they think they can ask these kinds of prices. Too many Android games out there offer all of this and charge a few dollars or less. If you don't want your games pirated, don't ask over triple the average market price for an android game.  Please get these games fixed so we can enjoy them!

FFV has been a classic RPG for 20+ years already for good reason (it falls in the top 10 of more than a few Top RPG lists) and the Android port does it justice.  Aside from the graphics overhaul it's gotten a new interface with dedicated on-screen buttons (for things like bringing up the menu, sprinting (which toggles), world map, and even a "Turbo A" stand-in ) and the game menu has been re-done as a touch screen interface.  The d-pad is replaced with an anywhere touch d-pad.  The movement is a little fidgety (accidentally stepping one or two steps an unintended direction while moving) but there's not many places where fine control is needed.  A single click (instead of click and drag) replaces the button for interacting with world objects. They've also added a "save anywhere" quicksave option and it autosaves fairly often.  I was a little leery of the $15 price point and would have preferred to see it down around $10 but it's undeniably  worth the price for a game you can easily spend 40-50 hours on.  I plan on picking up other games in the series once I finish this one.

This is a good game. I have thus far played FF3 and FF4 on Android and those were AWESOME games. At one point there were plans to remake FF5 and FF6 into 3D but it was scrapped for some odd reason. When you play a 3D legacy FF and a 2D legacy FF, there is a huge difference in how it feels. The 3D remakes (3 and 4) breathe a lot of new life into the game and give the game itself a lot of longevity. The 2D legacy games are a bit harder to stomach, as I'm learning now with FF5.  Overall this is a good game; not great like FF3 and FF4, but still good. I highly recommend it, but only after you have played FF3 and FF4. My only complaint: SE, Please, please PLEASE integrate cloud saving into your FF titles! Don't you know in this day and age most users play titles across multiple devices? And at some point users upgrade and get new devices and would not like to lose their save data because of that?

The 16-bit ff games are some of the greatest RPGs and games ever created. This one is no exception. Ff6 can't come fast enough.
